<subSubSection pageId="42" pageNumber="43" type="description">
<paragraph blockId="42.[151,1437,1249,2031]" pageId="42" pageNumber="43">
Morphology. D VI + I,8; A I,7; P 15–16 (
<bibRefCitation author="Kovacic, M." box="[695,875,1285,1312]" pageId="42" pageNumber="43" pagination="197 - 201" refId="ref57785" refString="Kovacic, M. (2002 b) A northern Adriatic population of Buenia affinis (Gobiidae). Cybium, 26, 197 - 201." type="journal article" year="2002">Kovačić 2002b</bibRefCitation>
). Small goby with subcylindrical body, laterally compressed towards caudal fin. Head slightly depressed and fairly long. Eyes large and close together, with narrow interorbital space. Caudal peduncle slender, clearly lower than body depth. Dorsal fins of similar height, first dorsal fin more or less with rounded edge with no elongate spines. Caudal fin rounded. Scales visible on upper body only by reticulate pattern of pigmentation along scale edges.
</paragraph>
<paragraph blockId="42.[151,1437,1249,2031]" pageId="42" pageNumber="43">
Live coloration. Body dorsally mainly brown or beige with 
<emphasis bold="true" pageId="42" pageNumber="43">4–5 well-defined, usually dark-edged, pale dorsal saddles, each terminating with a midlateral dark blotch; ventral half of body abruptly white with 10–12 narrow brownish bars</emphasis>
(
<figureCitation box="[341,426,1537,1563]" captionStart="FIGURE 41" captionStartId="37.[151,250,1968,1992]" captionTargetBox="[250,1338,1128,1945]" captionTargetId="figure-41@37.[250,1338,1128,1945]" captionTargetPageId="37" captionText="FIGURE 41. Live coloration in its natural habitat of Buenia affinis. Photos by R. Pillon, Rab Island, Croatia, Northern Adriatic Sea." figureDoi="http://doi.org/10.5281/zenodo.6601697" httpUri="https://zenodo.org/record/6601697/files/figure.png" pageId="42" pageNumber="43">Fig. 41</figureCitation>
). The cheek below orbit with darkened rectangular area formed by many small close-set dark dots. 
<emphasis bold="true" box="[268,968,1573,1599]" pageId="42" pageNumber="43">Typically 2 parallel dark dashes between eye and upper lip</emphasis>
(
<figureCitation box="[984,1078,1573,1599]" captionStart="FIGURE 41" captionStartId="37.[151,250,1968,1992]" captionTargetBox="[250,1338,1128,1945]" captionTargetId="figure-41@37.[250,1338,1128,1945]" captionTargetPageId="37" captionText="FIGURE 41. Live coloration in its natural habitat of Buenia affinis. Photos by R. Pillon, Rab Island, Croatia, Northern Adriatic Sea." figureDoi="http://doi.org/10.5281/zenodo.6601697" httpUri="https://zenodo.org/record/6601697/files/figure.png" pageId="42" pageNumber="43">Fig. 41a</figureCitation>
): 
<emphasis bold="true" pageId="42" pageNumber="43">lower one broad and always visible, the upper one thin and sometimes hard to see</emphasis>
(
<figureCitation box="[807,906,1609,1636]" captionStart="FIGURE 41" captionStartId="37.[151,250,1968,1992]" captionTargetBox="[250,1338,1128,1945]" captionTargetId="figure-41@37.[250,1338,1128,1945]" captionTargetPageId="37" captionText="FIGURE 41. Live coloration in its natural habitat of Buenia affinis. Photos by R. Pillon, Rab Island, Croatia, Northern Adriatic Sea." figureDoi="http://doi.org/10.5281/zenodo.6601697" httpUri="https://zenodo.org/record/6601697/files/figure.png" pageId="42" pageNumber="43">Fig. 41b</figureCitation>
). 
<emphasis bold="true" pageId="42" pageNumber="43">Iris and eye rim dark gray to dark brown, often with well-defined light gray dots</emphasis>
(
<figureCitation box="[634,719,1645,1671]" captionStart="FIGURE 41" captionStartId="37.[151,250,1968,1992]" captionTargetBox="[250,1338,1128,1945]" captionTargetId="figure-41@37.[250,1338,1128,1945]" captionTargetPageId="37" captionText="FIGURE 41. Live coloration in its natural habitat of Buenia affinis. Photos by R. Pillon, Rab Island, Croatia, Northern Adriatic Sea." figureDoi="http://doi.org/10.5281/zenodo.6601697" httpUri="https://zenodo.org/record/6601697/files/figure.png" pageId="42" pageNumber="43">Fig. 41</figureCitation>
). First dorsal fin very lightly pigmented, sometimes appearing transparent. When visible, fin with 2 white longitudinal stripes alternating with 3 brown-yellow bands; sometimes small blackish dot in the posterior fin corner. No specific sexual dichromatism reported (
<bibRefCitation author="Kovacic, M." box="[1143,1320,1717,1744]" pageId="42" pageNumber="43" pagination="197 - 201" refId="ref57785" refString="Kovacic, M. (2002 b) A northern Adriatic population of Buenia affinis (Gobiidae). Cybium, 26, 197 - 201." type="journal article" year="2002">Kovačić 2002b</bibRefCitation>
).
</paragraph>
